  <context>
    <background>
      The post-r1 synopsis (design.md §2.3 long-term item 11) flagged mutation testing as a high-value-paths priority for `Services/Ai/Safety/*` — the cross-matter privilege-leak surface (RB-T044-01 was exactly this). r2 Phase 1 fixed RB-T044-01 via inversion correction + regression test addition; the remaining question is: **how many other "obvious" assertions in this area are too weak to catch a similar bug?** Stryker.NET answers that empirically by generating mutated versions of the production code and checking whether each mutant is killed by an existing test.

      Per D-04, r2 ships **the score**, not the fix. The score informs r3's scope. If `Services/Ai/Safety/*` mutation score is high (>80%), r3 may not need expansion. If it's low (<60%), r3 expansion to `Capabilities/*` and `Chat/*` is well-motivated. If it's middling, the top-10 list directs r3 to the highest-leverage assertion repairs.

      Stryker.NET maturity (per spec.md Assumptions): v3.x is the current line. Compatibility with the test project's csproj structure is the load-bearing risk — if csproj uses unusual TestAdapter setups or non-standard project SDK, Stryker may fail. Document any issues; do not force-fit.
    </background>
    <dependencies>
      <dependency task="039" status="not-started">Phase 3 exit (all 20 ledger entries closed) — Phase 4 starts when Phase 3 exits</dependency>
    </dependencies>
  </context>

  <relevant-files>
    <file>projects/sdap.bff.api-test-suite-repair-r2/baseline/mutation-testing-Services-Ai-Safety-2026-08-XX.md</file>
